@ACos.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the arccosine (inverse cosine) of a number using the cosine of an angle.

@param {number} value Number or number list. A cosine of an angle, from -1 through 1.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The trigonometric arccosine of value. An angle, in radians, from 0 through pi.
This represents an angle between 0 and 180 degrees.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ACOS.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "returns 1.0471975511965979";
@ACos(.5);
@example
REM "returns [1.0471975511965979, 0.9272952180016123, 0.7953988301841436]";
@ACos(.5,.6,.7);

@ASin.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the arcsine (inverse sine) of a number using the sine of an angle.

@param {number} value Number or number list. A sine of an angle, from -1 through 1.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The trigonometric arcsine of value. An angle, in radians, from -pi/2 through pi/2.
This represents an angle between -90 and 90 degrees.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ASIN.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "returns 0.5235987755982989";
@ASin(.5);
@example
REM "returns [0.5235987755982989, 0.6435011087932844, 0.775397496610753]";
commat;ASin(.5,.6,.7);

@ATan.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the arc (inverse) tangent using the tangent of an angle.

@param {number} value Number or number list. A tangent of an angle, from -1 through 1.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The trigonometric arctan of value. An angle, in radians, from -pi/2 through pi/2.
This represents an angle between -90 and 90 degrees.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ATAN.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "returns 0.4636476090008061";
@ATan(.5);
@example
REM "returns [0.4636476090008061, 0.5404195002705842, 0.6107259643892086]";
@ATan(.5,.6,.7);

@ATan2.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the arc (inverse) tangent using the tangent x- and y-coordinates.

@param {number} x Number or number list. The denominator of the tangent value y / x.
@param {number} y Number or number list. The numerator of the tangent value y / x.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The trigonometric arctangent of y / x. An angle, in radians, from -pi through pi.
This represents an angle between -180 and 180 degrees, depending on the sign of x and y.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ATAN2.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "returns 0.7853981633974483";
@ATan2(1,1);
@example
REM "returns [0.7853981633974483, 0.7853981633974483, 0.7853981633974483]";
@ATan2([1,2,3],[1,2,3]);

@Abs.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the absolute (unsigned) value of one or more number(s).

@param {number} value Number or number list. The numbers whose absolute value is to be calculated.
    Any number whether positive or negative, whole or fractional, integer or real.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The absolute values of value.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ABS.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "returns 3";
@Abs(-3);
@example
REM "returns [3,4,5]";
@Abs(-3,-4,-5);

@AbstractSimple.!doc:
@category:Text
Creates a short abstract of a text or rich text field. Simpler and more
efficient than using @Abstract.
@param {TextOrTextList} bodyFields Any number of fields containing the text to abstract. May be text or rich text fields.
If Notes/Domino cannot locate a field by name, it uses the string literal instead.
Enclose each field name in quotes and separate multiple names with colons: "Sales":"Figures".
@returns {TextOrTextList} Returns the first 100 characters or first 2 paragraphs of text, whichever is smaller.
All newline and tab characters are converted into spaces, and all empty paragraphs (containing only a newline character) are ignored.
If the parameter is a single field, a text value is returned.
If the parameter is a list of field names, then a text list is returned with each list element containing the abstracted text of the corresponding field in the parameter list.
If a field parameter is of an invalid type, or can't be found, the text returned is the string of the field parameter.
@see For further information, see &nbsp;{@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ABSTRACTSIMPLE.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
Verse := "One bright day\n in the middle of\n the night"
REM { Returns "One bright day in the middle of" }
@AbstractSimple("Verse");
@example
Critics := "When asked to comment on the movie, the reviewer stated that it was one of the year's best, and certainly would find a place on many award lists."
REM { Returns "When asked to comment on the movie, the reviewer stated that it was one of the year's best, and cert" }
@AbstractSimple("Critics");

@Adjust.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Adjusts the specified time-date value by the number of years, months, days, hours, minutes, and/or seconds you specify.
The amount of adjustment may be positive or negative.

@param {DateOrDateList} dateOrDateList The Date or list of Dates you want to increment. This should be a single date, not a range.
@param {number} years The number of years to increment by.
@param {number} months The number of months to increment by.
@param {number} days The number of days to increment by.
@param {number} hours The number of hours to increment by.
@param {number} minutes The number of minutes to increment by.
@param {number} seconds The number of seconds to increment by.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The adjusted date string or list of adjusted date strings.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ADJUST.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "9/2/1997"};
@Adjust([06/30/95]; 2; 2; 2; 0; 0; 0);

@All.!doc:
@category:Document
Use @All in selection formulas, mail agents, paste agents, scheduled agents, or in any formula requiring a SELECT statement.
Notes/Domino appends SELECT @All to agents in contexts where @All is needed. All views default to a selection formula of SELECT @All.
@returns A promise that will resolve with the selected documents.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ALL.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "This example selects all documents in the database when used as a view selection formula";
SELECT @All
@example
REM "This formula, when used in a mail or paste agent, selects all documents and sets the Status field to \"Open.\"";
FIELD Status:="Open";SELECT @All

@AllChildren.!doc:
@category:Document
Includes all response documents at all levels for parent documents that match selection criteria.

&#64;AllChildren can only be used in a view selection or selective replication formula. It must be appended to the end of a selection
formula using the Boolean OR operator ("|"). Don't use it within complex expressions in a formula.
@returns A promise that will resolve with the selected documents plus their immediate responses.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ALLCHILDREN.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "This example selects all documents in the database with author Jim Thompson and their immediate responses when used as a view selection formula";
SELECT @Author = "Jim Thompson" | @AllChildren

@AllDescendants.!doc:
@category:Document
Includes all response and response-to-response documents for parents that match selection criteria.

&#64;AllDescendants can only be used in a view selection or selective replication formula. It must be appended to the end of a
selection formula using the Boolean OR operator ("|"). Don't use it within complex expressions in a formula.
@returns A promise that will resolve with the selected documents plus their responses and responses-to-responses, for as many
levels of response documents as exist.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ALLDESCENDANTS.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "This example selects all documents in the database with author Jim Thompson and all the responses for as many levels of response documents as exist when used as a view selection formula";
SELECT @Author = "Jim Thompson" | @AllDescendants

@Ascii.!doc:
@category:Text
Converts an LMBCS (Lotus Multi-Byte Character Set) string to an ASCII string.
@param {TextOrTextList} text An LMBCS string.
@param {boolean} [option] "ALLINRANGE" will return a null string ("") if any characters
in the original string cannot be represented by ASCII codes 32 to 127.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The original string, with each character converted to an ASCII-compliant character.
Any character that can't be represented by ASCII codes 32 to 127 is replaced with a question
mark (?). If you specify [ALLINRANGE] and there are characters that can't be represented by
ASCII codes 32 to 127, returns a null string ("").
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ASCII.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "Returns Cue";
@Ascii( "Çüé" );
@example
REM {Returns a null string ("") since the last 2 characters can't be represented by ASCII codes 32 to 127};
@Ascii("Çüé£¥";[ALLINRANGE]);
@example
REM {Returns "Cue??":"Cue":"Abc"};
@Ascii("Çüé£¥":"Çüé":"Abc");

@AttachmentNames.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns the operating system file names of any files attached to a document.
@param {boolean} excludeMIMEBody
@returns {string} File names of any files attached to a document. If there are multiple files attached,
the names are returned seperated by a semi-colon.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ATTACHMENTNAMES.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@Attachments.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns the number of files attached to a document.
@param {boolean} excludeMIMEBody
@returns {number} The number of files attached to the current document.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ATTACHMENTS.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@Author.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns a text list containing the names of the author(s) of the current document.
@returns {Array} All the authors of the current document. For authors with hierarchical names, Notes/Domino returns the abbreviated form of the name (as in Denise Lee/Research/Acme),
rather than the canonical form (CN=Denise Lee/OU=Research/O=Acme).
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_AUTHOR.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {If a document has one Authors field that contains: Mary Tsen, David Smith, Denise Lee/Research/Acme. This example returns: "Mary Tsen"; "David Smith"; "Denise Lee/Research/Acme" };
@Author;

@Begins.!doc:
@category:Text
Determines whether a particular substring is stored at the beginning of another string.

This function is case-sensitive. If the either parameter is a list, the function tests each element
of the second parameter against each element of the first parameter and returns 1 if any match occurs.

@param {TextOrTextList} within_text  The string to check
@param {TextOrTextList} find_text The string you want to search for at the beginning of string.
@returns {boolean} True if _find_text_ is contained within _within_text_, beginning from the first letter. False if not.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_BEGINS.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@Begins("Hi There";"Hi");
@example
REM {Returns "Don't Verify Signature"};
@If(@Begins("George":"Linda"; "Luigi":"Florence":"Henri"); "Verify signature"; "Don't Verify Signature");

@BrowserInfo.!doc:
@category:Information
@notimplemented:<strong>Not Implemented</strong>
Determines the capabilities of a Web client, that is you can determine the
properties of the browser for the current request.
@throws {Error} method not implemented
@see For further information, see &nbsp; {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_BROWSERINFO_8997.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@BusinessDays.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Returns the number of business days in one or more date ranges. Inclusive of the provided date ranges, and excluding the provided optional weekends and holidays.

@param {DateOrDateList} startDate Date as string or Date type, or list of Dates. The start of each date range.
@param {DateOrDateList} endDate Date as string or Date type, or list of Dates. The end of each date range.
@param {NumberOrNumberList} [daysToExclude] Numer or number list. Optional. Days of the week not counted as business days, where 1 is Sunday and 7 is Saturday.
    Decimal numbers are rounded to integers. Numbers other than 1-7 are ignored. (AKA Weekends)
@param {string|string[]|Date|Date[]} [datesToExclude] Date as string or Date type, or list of Dates. Optional. Dates not counted as business days. (AKA Holidays)
@returns {NumberOrNumberList} The number of days from startDates to endDates, inclusive, less daysToExclude and datesToExclude that fall within the date range.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_BUSINESSDAYS_FUNCTION.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 251, where HOLIDAYS include a list of 10 major US holidays in 2001};
@BusinessDays('01/01/2001'; '12/31/2001'; [1, 7]; HOLIDAYS);

@Char.!doc:
@category:Text
Converts an IBM Code Page 850 code number into the corresponding single character string.
@param {NumberOrNumberList} codeNumber Any number between 0 and 255. Non-integer numbers are truncated to integers.
If the parameter is a list, the function operates on each element of the list, and the return value is a list with the same number of elements.
@returns {TextOrTextList} A single character that corresponds to _codeNumber_.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_CHAR.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "A"};
@Char(65);
@example
REM {Returns "A":"a":"8"};
@Char(65 : 97 : 56);

@ClientType.!doc:
@category:Information
@notimplemented:<strong>Not Implemented</strong>
Returns a text string to differentiate Notes® clients and World Wide Web browsers.
@throws {Error} method not implemented
@see For further information, see &nbsp; {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_CLIENTTYPE_FUNCTION.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@CloseWindow.!doc:
@category:Window
Closes the current application window.
Depending on the platform the application is running under the behavior will vary:
For web apps, the browser window will be closed if the browser allows it, or if it does not then, it will navigate to the previous page (same behavior as Domino).
For mobile apps, the app will close if the platform allows it.
Same as the FileCloseWindow command
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_CLOSEWINDOW_COMMAND.html | hcltechsw.com}

@Command.!doc:
@category:Formula
Executes a Domino command.
@param {string} commandName The name of the &#64;Command you want to perform. See {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_COMMANDS_LISTED.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
for a list of available &#64;Commands.
@param {*} commandParameters Zero, one, or more parameters, depending on the &#64;Command you're calling. Separate parameters with semicolons.
@returns {number} 1 if the &#64;Command executes successfully or 0 if the &#64;Command does not execute successfully.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_COMMAND.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {Opens RECIPE.NSF to the 'Main' view, highlighting the first document whose value in the sort column matches the key 'Hot Chocolate'.};
@Command([FileOpenDatabase]; "server":"RECIPE.NSF"; "Main"; "Hot Chocolate" );

@Compare.!doc:
@category:Text
Compares the alphabetic order of the elements in two lists pair-wise.

@param textlist1 {string[]} A list of strings to compare. If _textlist1_ is shorter than _textlist2_, the last element in _textlist1_ is repeated until it reaches the same length as _textlist2_.
@param textlist2 {string[]} A list of strings to compare. If _textlist2_ is shorter than _textlist1_, the last element in _textlist2_ is repeated until it reaches the same length as _textlist1_.
@param {string|string[]} [options] You can use the following keywords to specify the compare options:
- "ACCENTSENSITIVE"
- "ACCENTINSENSITIVE"
- "CASESENSITIVE"
- "CASEINSENSITIVE"
- "PITCHSENSITIVE"
- "PITCHINSENSITIVE"

By default, the following keywords are used for the compare:
<pre>[CASESENSITIVE]:[ACCENTSENSITIVE]:[PITCHSENSITIVE]</pre>
@returns {number[]} Each element is the result of comparing the corresponding elements in the text lists, and is one of three values:
- 0 if the elements in the two lists are equal.
- -1 if the element in the first list is less than the element in the second list.
- 1 if the element in the first list is greater than the element in the second list.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_COMPARE.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@Compare("Boston"; "boston"; [CASESENSITIVE]);
@example
REM {Compares a list to the value "N" and displays the result. Boston and Moscow result in -1 (less than N), Tokyo results in 1 (greater than N), and n and N result in 0 (equal to N)};
list := "Boston" : "Tokyo" : "Moscow" : "N" : "n";
result := @text(@compare(list; "N"; [CaseInsensitive]));
@Prompt([OKCANCELLIST] : [NOSORT];
"Result"; ""; ""; list + " (" + result + ")")

@Compose.!doc:
@category:Create
Compose will make an empty document and then set it as the current document
The database must be open using fileOpenDatabase to compose a new document.
The document can be saved to the server using FileSave()
Composed documents not saved to the server are lost when the app closes.
@param {*} serverDatabase The name of the server and database where you want to create the document. For VoltMX, this is the name of the object service. For DRAPI, this is the name of the scope.
@param {string} formName The name of the form you want to use when creating the new document.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_COMPOSE.html | hcltechsw.com}
@returns {boolean} True if the document was composed. False if an error occurred trying to compose the document.
@example
REM "Composes a new MainTopic document in the current database";
@Command([Compose]; ""; "MainTopic")

@Contains.!doc:
@category:Text
Determines whether a substring is stored within a string.

This function is case-sensitive. If either parameter is a list, the function returns 1 if any element of
the first parameter contains any element of the second parameter.

@param {TextOrTextList} within_text The string(s) you want to search.
@param {TextOrTextList} find_text The string(s) you want to search for in string.
@returns {boolean} True if any substring is contained in one of the strings. False if no substrings are contained in any of the strings.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_CONTAINS.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@Contains("Hi There";"Th");
@example
REM {Returns 0};
@Contains("Tom":"Dick":"Harry";"Bob":"Roy");

@Context.!doc:
@category:Document
Gets the current API context (if ctx param is null or not supplied) or
Sets the API context to either database for local DOM, for those APIs
that require working with differents contexts such as GetField/SetField.

Note: this API is not derived from an existing Lotus Notes Formula function.
Instead, it is needed to set the acting context for the GetField and SetField functions.

@param {string} [ctx] the context to set: 'all', 'db', 'local'
@returns {string} the context
@example @Context("all");

@Cos.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Given an angle in radians, returns the cosine of the angle. In a right triangle,
the cosine of an acute angle is the ratio of the length of its adjacent side to
the length of the hypotenuse.

@param {number} angle Number or number list. An angle measured in radians for which you want the cosine.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The cosine of angle, from -1 to 1. Rounded to 15 decimal places.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_COS.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "returns 0.8775825618903728";
@Cos(.5);
@example
REM "returns [0.8775825618903728, 0.8253356149096783, 0.7648421872844885]";
@Cos(.5,.6,.7);

@Count.!doc:
@category:Lists
Calculates the number of text, number, or time-date values in a list. This function always returns a number to indicate the number of entries in the list.
@param {string[]|number[]|Date[]} items Text list, number list, or time-date list
@returns {number} The number of items in list.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_COUNT.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 2};
@Count('item1':'item2');
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@Count('string');

@Created.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Returns the time-date when the document was created.
@returns {Date|Error} Date. The date when the current document was created or error.data when the document or data is not available.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_CREATED.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "Returns Wed Aug 04 2021 12:23:17 GMT-0400 (Eastern Daylight Time)";
@Created();

@Day.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Extracts the day of the month from the specified date.

@param {DateOrDateList} dateOrDateList The date, as a string, Date object, or Array of Date objects or strings, of the day you are trying to find.
@returns {NumberOrNumberList} Number or number list. The number corresponding to the day of the month.
    Returns -1 if the time-date provided contains only a time value and not a date.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DAY.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 31};
@Day([01/31/2006]);
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@Day(@Date(1900; 0; 1));

@DbColumn.!doc:
@category:Database
Returns a column of values from a view or folder in a Domino® database.
@param {*} settings Indicates what type of database you are accessing. You can indicate a Domino® database with
either "Notes®" or "" (null string).
@param {*} serverDatabase The server location and file name of the database.
@param {string} viewName The name of the view in which to search. The view name must exactly match the full name
of the view as specified in the View properties (you can omit the alias). If the view cascades from another name
on the menu, include that name, too.
@param {number} [column=1] The column number within the view. Because Notes/Domino looks up information in the view
based on column numbers, you can only retrieve data that actually appears in the view.
@returns {Promise<any[]>} Promise that resolves to the values found in the view column that you indicated.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DBCOLUMN_NOTES_DATABASES.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@DbLookup.!doc:
@category:Database
Given a key value, looks in the specified view (or folder) and finds all documents containing the key value within the view.
@param {*} settings Indicates what type of database you are accessing. You can indicate a Domino® database with either ""
or "Notes®." Cache setting not supported.
@param {*} serverDatabase The server location and file name of the database.
@param {string} viewName The name of the view or folder in which to search.
@param {string} key Determines which document is actually read in order to retrieve a value. A document's key is the value
displayed in the first sorted column within the view. Note that if the column is re-sortable, results will depend on the current sort order.
@param {*} field The name of the field from which the data will be retrieved, once the correct document has been identified.
@param {string} keywords Additional keywords to modify the behavior of the lookup.
@returns {Promise<any[]>} Promise that resolves to the documents containing the key value within the view.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DBLOOKUP_NOTES_DATABASES.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@Debug.!doc:
@category:Information
Uses the console object's methods to display debug messages, * prepending them with a timestamp.
Defaults to console.log() if no type of logger is supplied.

@param {string} msg message
@param {string} [type] logger to employ:
'Error', 'Warning', 'Info', 'Debug', 'Log' from the console object,or javascript alert if type is Alert
@returns undefined if no logger available or object { ts:<timestamp string>, msg:<message> }
@example @Debug("An error occurred processing the formula", "Error");

@DeleteDocument.!doc:
@category:Document
Deletes the current document.
@returns Promise that will resolve with the response to deleting the document.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DELETEDOCUMENT.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "deletes those documents where the Status field equals \"Closed.\"";
FIELD Status:=@If(Status="Closed";@DeleteDocument;Status);

@DeleteField.!doc:
@category:Document
Deletes the value of an editable field.
@param {string} fieldName The name of a field in the current document.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DELETEFIELD.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@DialogBox.!doc:
@category:Document
Brings up a dialog box that displays the current document.
To customize the dialog box style, sknDialogWindowContainer, sknDialogWindowTitleContainer, and sknDialogWindowTitle skins need to be defined in the project.

@param {string} formFriendlyName. The name of the form to display in the dialog box.
@param {string | string[]} type. The type of the form to display in the dialog box.
@param {string} title. The title of the dialog box.
@returns {void}
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DIALOGBOX.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@Do.!doc:
@category:Logical
Evaluates expressions from left to right, and returns the value of the last
expression in the list.
No plans to implement - Convert to Native JS

@see For further information, see &nbsp;{@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DO.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@DoWhile.!doc:
@category:Logical
Executes one or more statements iteratively while a condition is true. Checks the condition after executing the statements.
No plans to implement - Convert to Native JS

@see For further information, see &nbsp;{@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DOWHILE_FUNCTION.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@DocChildren.!doc:
@category:Document
In a column or window title formula, returns the number of child documents or categories belonging
to the current document or category. Only immediate responses count as children. For example, the
responses to a main document are its children, but the responses to a response document are not.

The parameter descriptions are:
- defaultString The text to return. If a "%" is used in the string, it will be replaced with the number of
children documents or categories. Example: "% Responses."
- zero-string The text to return if the document or category has no children, such as "No Responses."
- one-string The text to return if the document or category has just one child, such as "One Response."

@param {string} string1 If this is the only argument, it is the defaultString. If there are
more than two arguments, this is the zero-string.
@param {string} string2 If there are two arguments, it is the defaultString. If there are
three arguments, this is the one-string.
@param {string} string3 This is the defaultString.
@returns {string} The return value depends on how you call &#64;DocChildren:
- numChildren If &#64;DocChildren is called with no parameters, then the number of child documents belonging to
the current document or category is returned. You cannot convert special text to a number.
- childString If &#64;DocChildren is called with one or more parameters, it returns the appropriate string, based
on the number of child documents belonging to the current document or category. You cannot convert special text
to a number.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DOCCHILDREN.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {This example returns 3 if there are 3 responses};
@DocChildren;
@example
REM {This example returns 3 Responses. The appropriate number is substituted for %. If the document doesn't have any responses, this formula returns 0 Responses.};
@DocChildren("% Responses");
@example
REM {This example returns 3 Responses. This time, if the document doesn't have any responses, the formula returns the message No Responses.};
@DocChildren("No Responses";"% Responses");
@example
REM {This example returns There are 3 Responses. If the document has one response, the message is 1 Response; if the document has no responses, the message is No Responses.};
@DocChildren("No Responses";"1 Response";"There are % Responses.");

@DocDescendants.!doc:
@category:Document
In a column or window title formula, returns the number of descendant documents or subcategories belonging to the current
document or category. Where &#64;DocChildren only counts direct descendants, &#64;DocDescendants counts all descendants, regardless
of level.

The parameter descriptions are:
- defaultString The text to return. If a "%" is used in the string, it will be replaced with the number of
descendant documents or categories. Example: "% Responses."
- zero-string The text to return if the document or category has no descendant, such as "No Responses."
- one-string The text to return if the document or category has just one descendant, such as "One Response."

@param {string} string1 If this is the only argument, it is the defaultString. If there are
more than two arguments, this is the zero-string.
@param {string} string2 If there are two arguments, it is the defaultString. If there are
three arguments, this is the one-string.
@param {string} string3 This is the defaultString.
@returns {string} The return value depends on how you call &#64;DocDescendants:
- numDescendants If &#64;DocDescendants is called with no parameters, then the number of descendant documents belonging to
the current document or category is returned.
- descendantsString If &#64;DocDescendants is called with one or more parameters, it returns the appropriate string, based
on the number of descendant documents belonging to the current document or category.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DOCDESCENDANTS.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {This example returns 3 if there are 3 responses};
@DocDescendants;
@example
REM {This example returns 3 Responses. The appropriate number is substituted for %. If the document doesn't have any responses, this formula returns 0 Responses.};
@DocDescendants("% Responses");
@example
REM {This example returns 3 Responses. This time, if the document doesn't have any responses, the formula returns the message No Responses.};
@DocDescendants("No Responses";"% Responses");
@example
REM {This example returns There are 3 Responses. If the document has one response, the message is 1 Response; if the document has no responses, the message is No Responses.};
@DocDescendants("No Responses";"1 Response";"There are % Responses.");

@DocLevel.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns a text string that represents the level of the document or category.
@returns The level of the document or category.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DOCLEVEL.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {This example of a main document in a category returns 2}
@DocLevel;
@example
REM {This example of a response document in a category returns 3}
@DocLevel;

@DocNumber.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns a string representing the entry number of the current document or category. For example, 2.3 indicates
that the document is the third entry following the second entry.
@param {string} [separator] Optional. Indicates a separator to be used in the document number instead of "." (period); must be one character.
An empty string (""), Tells the function to return the least significant item of the document number (in other words, its rightmost component).
@returns The value that represents the document number of the document or category in the view.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DOCNUMBER.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {This example returns 37.1.3 for entry 37.1.3}
@DocNumber;
@example
REM {This example returns 37-1-3 for entry 37.1.3}
@DocNumber("-");
@example
REM {This example returns 3 for entry 37.1.3}
@DocNumber("");

@DocParentNumber.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns a string that represents the entry number of the parent view entry. Both the current view entry and the parent can be either documents or categories.
@param {string} [separator] Optional. Indicates a separator to be used in the parent document number instead of "." (period); must be one character.
An empty string (""), Tells the function to return the least significant item of the parent document number (in other words, its rightmost component).
@returns The value that represents the parent document number of the document or category in the view.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DOCPARENTNUMBER.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {This example returns 37.1 for entry 37.1.3}
@DocParentNumber;
@example
REM {This example returns 37-1 for entry 37.1.3}
@DocParentNumber("-");
@example
REM {This example returns 1 for entry 37.1.3}
@DocParentNumber("");

@DocSiblings.!doc:
@category:Document
In a column or window title formula, returns a string that represents the total number of entries at the same level as a view entry (document or category).
The returned total includes the document itself. For example, if the document is entry 8.2, and entries 8.1, 8.3, and 8.4 also exist, then there are four
document siblings.
@returns {string} The number of entries at the same level as the document or category.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DOCSIBLINGS.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {returns Response 1 of 4 to Current Vacation Policy if the document is one of four responses to a document with the string Current® Vacation Policy in the Topic field};
@If(@IsNewDoc;"New Document";"Response" + @DocNumber(" ") + " of " + @DocSiblings + " to " + Topic)

@DocumentUniqueID.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns the universal ID, which uniquely identifies a document across all replicas of a database. In text format, the universal ID is a 32-character combination of hexadecimal digits (0-9, A-F).

The universal ID is also known as the unique ID or UNID.
@returns {string} The universal id
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_DOCUMENTUNIQUEID.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "Displays the UNID of each document in the view"
@Text(@DocumentUniqueID);

@Elements.!doc:
@category:Lists
Calculates the number of text, number, or time-date values in a list. This function always returns a number to indicate the number of entries in the list.
@param {string[]|number[]|Date[]} items Text list, number list, or time-date list
@returns {number} The number of items in the list.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ELEMENTS.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 2};
@Elements("item1":"item2");

@Ends.!doc:
@category:Text
Determines if a substring is at the end of a string.

This function is case-sensitive. If the either parameter is a list, the function tests each element
of the second parameter against each element of the first parameter and returns 1 if any match occurs.

@param {TextOrTextList} within_text The string to search.
@param {TextOrTextList} find_text The string to search for at the end of _within_text_.
@returns {boolean} True indicates that the _find_text_ is at the end of _within_test_. Otherwise false if not.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ENDS.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@Ends("Hi There";"re");
@example
REM {Returns "Verify signature"};
@If(@Ends("Mike Irons";"Owens":"Irons":"Baker");"Verify signature"; "Don't Verify Signature");

@Environment.!doc:
@category:Miscellaneous
Sets or returns an environment variable stored in a formula.

@param {string} key The name of the environment variable you want to retrieve or set.
@param {string} [value] Optional value to set for the key. If not specified, the value of the key will be returned.
@returns {string|null} If value not specified, the value of the environment variable. If value was specified,
the encrypted value of the environment variable that was set.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ENVIRONMENT.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "Returns the value of the environment variable 'myVar'";
@Environment("myVar");
@example
REM "Sets the value of the environment variable 'myVar' to 'myValue'";
@Environment("myVar", "myValue");

@Eval.!doc:
@category:Formula
At run-time, compiles and runs each element in a text expression as a formula.
Returns the result of the last formula expression in the list or an error if an
error is generated by any of the formula expressions in the list.
@param {string} textExpressions Any text expressions that you want &#64;Eval to evaluate.
Surround the text expression to be evaluated with braces ({ }) or quotation marks (" ").
If you use quotation marks, escape quotes around individual text expressions within the formula with back-slashes (\).
If you use braces, escape the right brace. Use the plus sign (+) to concatenate text expressions.
@returns {Promise<any>} The value of the last expression.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_EVAL.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {Returns "rebar"}
x := "re";
@Eval({x + "bar"});

@Exp.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns e (approximately 2.718282) raised to the power of a given number.

@param {number} power Number or number list. The power to which you want to raise e.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The number e raised to the power of the parameter. (this value can contain up to 14 decimal places).
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_EXP.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "returns 2.718281828459045";
@Exp(1);
@example
REM "returns [2.718281828459045, 2.718281828459045]";
@Exp(1,1);

@Explode.!doc:
@category:Lists
Returns a text list composed of the elements of a text string or date range.
- If you specify a text string, elements are defined as sequences of characters separated by separator characters and newlines.
- If you specify a time-date range, elements are defined as individual days within the range.
@param {TextOrTextList|DateRangeOrDateRangeList} stringOrDateRange Can be one of the following:
- The string that you want to make into a text list.
- The range of dates that you want to make into a text list. Specify a valid date-time range, not a string
representation of one. For example, &#64;Explode( "05/01/96 - 05/02/96" ) is invalid because the parameter is a string.
Use &#64;Explode( [05/01/96 - 05/02/96] ).
@param {string} [separators] One or more characters that define the end of an element in string. The default
separators are " ,;" (space, comma, semicolon), which means that Domino® adds a new element to the text list
each time a space, comma, or semicolon occurs in the original string. When you use more than one character to
specify separators, each character defines one separator. For example, the specification "and" breaks the string
at each occurrence of "a," "n," and "d"; it does not break the string at each occurrence of the word "and."
The newline is a separator, regardless of the specification of this parameter, unless newlineAsSeparator is
specified as False.
@param {boolean} [includeEmpties] Specify True (1) to place an empty string ("") in the returned list when a
separatorappears at the beginning or end of the string, or two separators appear consecutively in the string.
Specify False (0) to not include empty list elements for leading, trailing, and consecutive separators. Defaults to False.
@param {boolean} [newlineAsSeparator] Specify True (1) to treat the newline as a separator. Specify False (0) to not
treat the newline as a separator. Defaults to True.
@returns {string[]} A list containing each element found in string, or each date found in dateRange.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_EXPLODE.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns a, b, and c in a list};
@Explode("a,b,c");
@example
REM {Returns 07/02/2023; 07/03/2023; 07/04/2023; 07/05/2023};
@Explode([07/02/2023 - 07/05/2023]);

@Failure.!doc:
@category:Logical
Returns text that indicates that input to a field does not meet validation.

@param {string} message The error message to be displayed to the user.
@returns {string} The message indicating the failure.
@see For further informaton, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_FAILURE.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@False.!doc:
@category:Logical
Returns the number 0 (false).

@returns {number} The number 0 (false).
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_FALSE.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@FileCloseWindow.!doc:
@category:File
Closes the current application window.
Depending on the platform the application is running under, the behavior will vary:
- For web apps, the browser window will be closed if the browser allows it. If not, it will navigate to the previous page (same behavior as Domino).
- For mobile apps, the app will close if the platform allows it.
Same as the CloseWindow command.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_FILECLOSEWINDOW.html | hcltechsw.com}

@FileDir.!doc:
@category:Text
Returns the directory portion of a path name, that is, the path name minus the file name.
@param {TextOrTextList} pathname Path name of a file.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The directory part of the path name.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_FILEDIR.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "c:\"};
@FileDir("c:\\europe.dat");
@example
REM {Returns "c:\" : "\"};
@FileDir("c:\\market\\data\\europe.dat":"\\europe.dat");
@example
REM "Returns Null";
@FileDir("europe.dat");

@FileOpenDatabase.!doc:
@category:File
Opens the specified database to the specified view, highlighting the first document whose value in the sort
column matches the key. You specify a database using its server and file name.
@param {*} serverDatabase The server location and file name of the database.
@param {string} [viewName] The name of the view you want to open in the database. If you omit the name of the
view, the database opens to its default view; or, if the user has opened the database before,
to the last view used by that user.
@param {*} [key] Indicates which document you want Notes® to scroll to when it opens viewName.
If you omit the key, no document is selected.
@returns Promise that resolves to True if the document was open.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_FILEOPENDATABASE.html | hcltechsw.com}

@FilePrint.!doc:
@category:File
Prints the currently open or selected document(s), or the current view.
@param {string} numCopies - Number of copies to print.
@param {string} fromPage - Starting page number.
@param {string} toPage - Ending page number.
@param {string} ifDraft - Print in draft mode.
@param {string} ifView - Print the current view.
@param {string} formName - Name of the form to print.
@param {string} breakType - Type of page break.
@param {string} ifReset - Reset the printer settings.
@param {any} startDate - Start date for printing.
@param {any} endDate - End date for printing.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_FILEPRINT.html | hcltechsw.com}

@FileSave.!doc:
@category:File
Save the current Notes database file.
@returns Promise that resolves to true if the document was saved.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_FILESAVE.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "saves and closes form1 and opens form2 in edit mode";
dbname := @DbName;
@Command([FileSave]);
@Command([CloseWindow]);
@Command([Compose]; dbname; "form2");

@FloatEq.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Compares two numbers for equality within a confidence range.

@param {number} number1 Number or number list. Any numeric value.
@param {number} number2 Number or number list. Any numeric value.
@param {number} confidence Number or number list. Optional (default is 0.0001).
@returns {number} Returns 1 (true) if the difference of the numbers is less than the confidence
    range. Returns 0 (false) if the difference of the numbers exceeds or is equal to
    the confidence range.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_FLOATEQ.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "returns false";
@FloatEq(2.22, 2.24, 0.01);
@example
REM "returns true";
@FloatEq(2.22, 2.24, 0.03);
@example
REM "returns true";
@FloatEq([2.22, 2.24], [2.25, 2.26], 0.04);

@For.!doc:
@category:Logical
Executes one or more statements iteratively while a condition remains true. Executes an initialization statement.
Checks the condition before executing the statements and executes an increment statement after executing the statements.
No plans to implement - Convert to Native JS

@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_FOR_FUNCTION.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@GetCurrentTimeZone.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Returns the current operating system's time zone settings in canonical time zone format.

@returns {string} Canonical time zone representing the time zone settings of the operating system.
     If the Notes time zone string is not found, the JavaScript time zone name is returned.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_GETCURRENTTIMEZONE.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "Z=5$DO=1$DL=3 2 1 11 1 1$ZX=40$ZN=Eastern" if in the Eastern Time Zone};
@GetCurrentTimeZone();

@GetDocField.!doc:
@category:Database
Given the unique ID of a document, returns the contents of a specific field on
that document. The document must reside in the current database.
@param {string} documentUNID The unique ID of a document.
@param {string} fieldName The name of a field on the document.
@returns Promise that resolves to the contents of the field on the specified document.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_GETDOCFIELD.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@GetField.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns the value of a specified field, as per the API context (db or local)
Note: if context is set to all, return value from db if found before attempting local DOM
@param {string} fieldName The name of a field in the current document.
@returns {*} The value of the specified field or "" if error or field not found.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_GETFIELD.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@GetFieldType.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns the field type. The current document is used from the default view.
@param {string} fieldName The name of a field whose type should be returned.
@returns {any} Returns the type of the field. Possible return values are:
'string', 'number', 'date', 'richtext', 'string[]', 'number[]', 'date[]', 'richtext[]', or '[]'

@GetHTTPHeader.!doc:
@category:Network
@notimplemented:<strong>Not Implemented</strong>
In a Web application, returns the value of an HTTP header from the browser
client request being processed by the server.
@throws {Error} method not implemented
@see For further information, see &nbsp; {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_GETHTTPHEADER.html | www.hcltechsw.com }
@TODO this needs to be implemented

@HashPassword.!doc:
@category:Miscellaneous
Encodes a string.

@param {string} text. The string that you want to encode.
@returns {string} encodedString.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_HASHPASSWORD.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@Hour.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Extracts the number of the hour (0 through 23) from a specified Date.

@param {DateOrDateList} dateOrDateList The date, as a string, Date object, or Array of Date objects or strings, of the hour that you want to extract.
@returns {NumberOrNumberList} Number or Number list. A number (or list) representing the hour contained in dateOrDateList. Hours are represented as 0 through 23 for 12 AM through 11 PM.
    Returns -1 if the time-date provided contains only a date and not a time value.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_HOUR.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@Hour([1/1/1900 1:00]);
@example
REM {Returns 8};
@Hour(@Date(95; 11; 20; 8; 58; 12);

@If.!doc:
@category:Logical
Specifies a logical test to perform and returns the specified value determined by the test.

No plans to implement - Convert to Native JS
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_IF.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@IfError.!doc:
@category:Logical
Returns a value you specify if a formula evaluates to an error or null string ("") if no value is specified;
otherwise, returns the result of the formula.

@param {*} value The argument that is checked for an error.
@param {*} value_if_error The value to return if the formula evaluates to an error. The following error types are evaluated: #N/A, #VALUE!, #REF!, #DIV/0!, #NUM!, #NAME?, or #NULL!.
@returns {*} The value you specify if a formula evaluates to an error or null string ("") if no value is specified;
otherwise, returns the result of the formula.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_IFERROR_FUNCTION.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@Implode.!doc:
@category:Lists
Concatenates all members of a text list and returns a text string.
@param {TextOrTextList} textlistValue List containing the items you want to concatenate into a single string.
If you send a single piece of text instead of a list, &#64;Implode returns the text unaltered.
@param {string} separator Used to separate the values in the concatenated string. If you don't specify a _separator_,
a space is used.
@returns {string} String containing each member of textListValue, separated by separator.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_IMPLODE.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns Minneapolis Detroit Chicago};
@Implode("Minneapolis":"Detroit":"Chicago");
@example
REM {Returns Minneapolis,Detroit,Chicago};
@Implode("Minneapolis":"Detroit":"Chicago";",");

@Integer.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Truncates the values in a number or number list at the whole number, leaving off
any decimals.

@param {number} value Number or number list. The value(s) you want to truncate.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The truncated value(s).
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_INTEGER.html | www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "returns 5";
@Integer(5.5);
@example
REM "returns [5, 6, 7]";
@Integer(5.5,6.6,7.7);

@IsAvailable.!doc:
@category:Document
Checks a document for the existence of a field.
@param {*} field The field to check
@returns True indicates that the field is contained in the document. False indicates that the field is not contained in the document.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISAVAILABLE.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "This formula returns the value of the Dept field if it exists in the document, otherwise it returns Consultant";
@If(@IsAvailable(Dept);Dept;"Consultant");
@example
REM "This formula returns the value of the field named Topic if it exists in the document, otherwise it returns the value contained in the field named Subject.";
@If(@IsAvailable(Topic);Topic;Subject);
@example
REM "This formula, when added to a hotspot button, checks for the existence of the Priority field in a form, then sets its value if found or creates a new Priority field and sets its value, if not found";
@If(@IsAvailable(Priority);@SetField("Priority";"High");FIELD Priority := "High");

@IsCategory.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns a specified string if the current document of a view is defined as a category.
@param [trueString] {string} A string to return if an item in the view row is a category.
@param [falseString] {string} A string to return if no item in the row is a category.
@returns If no parameters are specified, the function returns an asterisk (&#42;) if the current document is a category.
Otherwise returns an empty string. If trueString is specified, returns trueString instead
of asterisk (&#42;). If falseString is specified, returns falseString instead of an empty string.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISCATEGORY.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {This example returns * if the row is a category, or nothing if the row is not a category.}
@IsCategory;
@example
REM {This example returns C if the row is a category, or nothing if the row is not a category.}
@IsCategory("C");
@example
REM {This example returns Y if the row is a category, or N if the row is not a category.}
@IsCategory("Y";"N");

@IsError.!doc:
@category:Information
Returns 1 (True) if the value is an &#64;ERROR value, returns 0 (False) if not
an error.
@param {*} value
@returns {boolean} True if the value is an &#64;ERROR value or false if not
@see For further information, see &nbsp; {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISERROR.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@IsMember.!doc:
@category:Lists
Indicates if a piece of text (or a text list) is contained within another text list. The function is case-sensitive.
@param {TextOrTextList} textValue The text or text list used to check if it is contained in another text list.
@param {string} textListValue The text list to check if it contains the text or text list.
@returns True if the _textValue_ is contained in _textListValue_ or false if not. If both parameters are lists,
returns true if all elements of _textValue_ are contained in _textListValue_.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISMEMBER.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {This example returns 1};
@IsMember("computer";"printer":"computer":"monitor");
@example
REM {This example returns 0};
@IsMember("computer":"Notes";"Notes":"printer":"monitor");

@IsNewDoc.!doc:
@category:Document
For a document being edited, indicates if the document has been saved to disk.
@returns 1 (True) if the document being edited has not yet been saved to disk. Returns 0 (False) if the document has been saved.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISNEWDOC.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@IsNotMember.!doc:
@category:Lists
Indicates if a text string (or a text list) is not contained within another text list. The function is case-sensitive.
@param {TextOrTextList} textValue The text or text list used to check if it is not contained in another text list.
@param {string} textListValue The text list to check if it does not contain the text or text list.
@returns True if the _textValue_ is not contained in _textListValue_ or false if it is. If both parameters are lists,
returns true if all elements of _textValue_ are not contained in _textListValue_.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISNOTMEMBER.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {This example returns 1};
@IsNotMember("keyboard";"printer":"computer":"monitor");
@example
REM {This example returns 0};
@IsNotMember("computer";"printer":"computer":"monitor");

@IsNull.!doc:
@category:Logical
Tests for a null value. Returns true only if a value is a single text value that
is null, otherwise it returns false. This function also returns false if the
value is an error.

@param {*} value The value to test for null text value.
@returns {boolean} True if value is null, otherwise false.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISNULL.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@IsNumber.!doc:
@category:Text
Returns if a given value is a number (or an array of numbers).
@param {*} value A single value or list of values.
@returns {boolean} True if the value is a number or an array of numbers. False if the value is not a number or an array of numbers.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISNUMBER.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@IsNumber(123);
@example
REM {Returns 0};
@IsNumber("123");
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@IsNumber(-345:2.78:997:.7);

@IsResponseDoc.!doc:
@category:Document
Indicates whether a document is a response to another document.
@returns Returns 1 (True) if the document is a response document. Returns 0 (False) if the document is not a response document.
Returns 0 for new documents, since &#64;IsResponseDoc doesn't recognize a document type until after the document is saved
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISRESPONSEDOC.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns Response if the document is a response; Topic if the document is not a response.}
@If(@IsResponseDoc;"Response";"Topic");

@IsText.!doc:
@category:Text
Indicates whether a value is text (or a text list).
@param {*} value Any data type. Any value. Any list of values.
@returns {boolean} True if the value is text or an array of text. False if the value is not text or an array of text.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISNUMBER.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@IsText("New Orleans":"Houston":"Dallas":"Mobile.");
@example
REM {Returns 0};
@IsText("123":5:"674");

@IsTime.!doc:
@category:Text
Returns whether a value is a time-date (or an array of time-date).
@param {*} value Any value.
@returns {boolean} 1 (True) if the value is a time-date or an array of time-date. 0 (False) if the value is not a time-date or an array of time-date.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISTIME.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@IsTime("08/31/2002");
@example
REM {Returns 0};
@IsTime("123");

@IsUnavailable.!doc:
@category:Document
Indicates whether a field name exists in a document.

CAUTION: Do not confuse &#64;IsUnavailable with &#64;Unavailable. &#64;Unavailable deletes fields and can cause serious damage if used unintentionally in place of &#64;IsUnavailable.

@param {*} field The field to check.
@returns True indicates that the field is not contained in the document. False indicates that the field is contained in the document.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ISUNAVAILABLE.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns Consultant if the field Dept does not exist; if Dept does exist, the value contained in Dept is returned.}
@If(@IsUnavailable(Dept);"Consultant";Dept);

@Keywords.!doc:
@category:Lists
Given two text lists, returns only those items from the second list that are found in the first list.

This function is case-sensitive; you must standardize the case of _textList1_ and _textList2_. If you want case
to be ignored (use &#64;LowerCase, &#64;ProperCase or &#64;UpperCase).

@param {string[]} textList1 A list of items.
@param {string[]} textList2 A list of items that you want to compare to _textList1_.
@param {string} [separator] One or more characters to be used as delimiters between words. &#64;Keywords considers
each character (not the combination of multiple characters) to be a delimiter. For example, defining separator
as ". ," (period, space, comma) tells the function to separate the text at each period, space, and comma into
separate words.

When you do not specify a separator, the following word delimiters are used by default:
?. ,!;:[](){}"<> (question mark, period, space, comma, exclamation point, semicolon, colon, (brackets, parentheses,
braces, quotation mark, and angle brackets)

A null separator, represented by an empty string (""), tells the function to use no delimiters.
@returns {string[]} When a _separator_ is in effect, either by default or specification, &#64;Keywords parses _textList1_
into words delimited by the separator and returns any word that exactly matches a keyword in _textList2_. When
no separator is in effect (when you specify a null separator), &#64;Keywords returns any sequence of characters in
_textList1_ that matches a keyword specified in _textList2_.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_KEYWORDS.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {This returns Harvard;Yale};
@Keywords(@ProperCase("EPA Head speaks at Harvard and yale":"The UCLA Chancellor Retires":"Ohio State wins big game":"Reed and University of Oregon share research facilities");"Harvard":"Brown":"Stanford":"Yale":"Vassar":"UCLA");
@example
REM {This formula returns "", a null string};
@Keywords("EPA Head speaks at Harvard,Yale":"UCLA Chancellor Retires":"Ohio State wins big game":"Reed and University of Oregon share research facilities";"harvard":"brown":"stanford":"vassar":"ucla");
@example
REM {This formula returns Harvard;Yale. It searches textList1 for the textList2 keywords that follow either a comma or a space};
@Keywords("EPA Head speaks at Harvard, Yale hosts her next month":"UCLA Chancellor Retires":"Ohio State wins big game":"Reed and University of Oregon share research facilities";"Harvard":"Brown":"Stanford":"Yale":"UCLA";", ");

@LDAPServer.!doc:
@category:Information
@notimplemented:<strong>Not Implemented</strong>
Returns the URL and port number of the LDAP listener in the current domain.
Notes® looks for this information in several places, following this search
sequence:
1. Searches on the current server.
2. Searches for the notes.ini variable labeled LDAPSERVER=.
3. Queries the administration server, which runs the LDAP service automatically, by default.
@throws {Error} method not implemented
@see For further information, see &nbsp; {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LDAPSERVER_FUNCTION.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@LanguagePreference.!doc:
@category:Information
Returns user's specified preferred language setting.

@param {Text} keyword Specify a category for which you would like to get the preferred language. The following categories are available:
    [REGION]         Returns preferred language for region.
    [CONTENT]        Returns preferred language for database contents.
    [ALTERNATENAME]  Returns preferred language for alternate name.
@returns {TextOrTextList} Text or Text list that represents the language and country code for user's preferred setting.
    [REGION] language is set as the default.
    If @LanguagePreference cannot find the language setting for the specified category, it returns the language for [REGION].
@see For further information, see &nbsp;{@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LANGUAGEPREFERENCE_FORMULA.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {Returns 'fr-CA' if the language settings is set to French(Canada).}
@LanguagePreference([REGION]);
@example
REM {Returns 'fr'}
@LanguagePreference([ALTERNATENAME]);

@Left.!doc:
@category:Text
Searches a string from left to right and returns the leftmost characters of the string.
@param {TextOrTextList} stringToSearch The string where you want to find the leftmost characters.
@param {number|string} param If a number, the number of characters to return. If the number is 2, the first two characters of the string are
returned; if the number is 5, the first five characters are returned, and so on. If the number is negative, the entire string
is returned.

If a string, A substring of stringToSearch. Returns the characters to the left of subString. It finds subString by searching
stringToSearch from left.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The leftmost characters in stringToSearch. The number of characters returned is determined by param.
Returns "" if param is a string and it is not found in stringToSearch.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LEFT.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "Len"};
@Left("Lennard Wallace";3);
@example
REM {Returns "Lennard Wal"};
@Left("Lennard Wallace";"la");

@LeftBack.!doc:
@category:Text
Searches a string from right to left and returns a substring.
@param {TextOrTextList} stringToSearch The string where you want to find the leftmost characters.
@param {number|string} param If a number, counting from right to left, the number of characters to skip. All the characters to the left
of that number of characters are returned. If the number is negative, the entire string is returned.

If a string, A substring of stringToSearch. All the characters to the left of startString are returned.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The leftmost characters in stringToSearch. The number of characters returned is determined by either numToSkip or startString.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LEFTBACK.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "Lennard Wall"};
@LeftBack("Lennard Wallace";3);
@example
REM {Returns "Lennard"};
@LeftBack("Lennard Wallace"; " ");

@Length.!doc:
@category:Text
Returns the number of characters in a text string.
@param {TextOrTextList} text A string or array of strings with the lenght you want to find.
@returns {NumberOrNumberList} If _text_ is a string, returns the number of characters in the specified string, including spaces and punctuation.
If text is a list of strings, returns the number of characters for each string in the array.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LENGTH.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 45};
@Length("The boy crossed the wide, but gentle, stream.");
@example
REM {Returns 0 : 5 : 3};
@Length("": "abcde": "xyz" );

@Like.!doc:
@category:Text
Matches a string with a pattern. It is case-sensitive.

@param {TextOrTextList} text The value to be tested to see if it matches _pattern_.
@param {TextOrTextList} pattern The sequence of characters to search for within _text_. May also contain any of the wildcard characters listed as follows:
   - C where C is any character. Matches any single, non-special, character C.
   - _ (Underscore) Matches any single character.
   - % Matches any sequence of zero or more characters.
@param {string} [escape] A character to use before a wildcard character to indicate that it should be treated literally.
@returns {boolean} True if the _pattern_ matches the _text_. False if the _pattern_ does not matches the _text_.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LIKE.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Return false. The underscore matches only a single character.};
@Like( "A big test" ; "A_test");
@example
REM {Returns true because the match is true for one element of the first parameter.};
@Like( "A big test" : "A big exam" ; "%test" );
@example
REM {Returns true. The first percent matches "100." The "/%" matches the percent sign because "/" is specified as the escape character. The last percent matches "ement."};
@Like( "A 100% improvement" ; "A %/% improv%" ; "/" )

@Ln.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the natural log of a number. Natural logs use e (approximately 2.718282)
as their base.

@param {number} value Number or number list. May be any value greater than 0, and can contain up to 15 decimal places.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The natural log of number.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LN.html | www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "returns 1.6094379124341003";
@Ln(5);
@example
REM "returns [1.6094379124341003, 1.791759469228055, 1.9459101490553132]";
@Ln(5,6,7);

@Locale.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Returns information about language codes.

@param {TextOrTextList} action Text or text list with action keyword. One of the following:
    [NotesLocale] without locale-tag returns a text list containing all the content language codes.
    [NotesLocale] with locale-tag returns a text list or value containing each specified content language code,
          or a null string if the code is not recognized. A code is recognized if it is exact regardless of case.
          If the language is recognized but not the country or region, the language code alone is returned.
    [AltNameLocale] without locale-tag returns a text list containing all the alternate name language codes.
    [AltNameLocale] with locale-tag returns a text list or value containing each specified alternate user language code,
          or a null string if the code is not recognized. A code is recognized if it is exact regardless of case.
          The country or region is ignored where it is not part of the alternate user language code (most cases).
    [LanguageName] with locale-tag returns a text list or value spelling out the language for each specified language code,
          or a null string if the code is not recognized.
    [CountryName] with locale-tag returns a text list or value spelling out the country or region for each specified language code,
          or a null string if the code has no country or region, or it is not recognized.
    [LocaleName] with locale-tag returns a text list or value spelling out the language and country (or region), if applicable,
          for each specified language code, or a null string if the code is not recognized. The country or region is in parentheses
          and immediately (no space) follows the language.
    [LocaleName] : [NotesLocale] (concatenating these two keywords) returns a text list containing, for each content language code,
          the language name, the country or region name in parentheses, a vertical bar, and the language code. This list can be used in a keyword field
          where the locale name is the name and the language code is the alias.
    [LocaleName] : [AltNameLocale] (concatenating these two keywords) returns a text list containing, for each alternate name language code,
          the language name, the country or region name in parentheses, a vertical bar, and the language tag.
          This list can be used in a keyword field where the locale name is the name and the language code is the alias.
@param {TextOrTextList} [localeTag] A language code or list of language codes.
    af,ar,ar-AE,ar-BH,ar-DZ,ar-EG,ar-JO,ar-KW,ar-LB,ar-MA,ar-OM,ar-QA,ar-SA,ar-TN,ar-YE,be,bg,ca,cs,cy,
    da,de,de-AT,de-CH,de-DE,de-LI,de-LU,el,en,en-AU,en-CA,en-GB,en-HK,en-IE,en-IN,en-JM,en-NZ,en-PH,en-SG,
    en-US,en-ZA,es,es-AR,es-BO,es-CL,es-CO,es-CR,es-DO,es-EC,es-ES,es-GT,es-HN,es-MX,es-NI,es-PA,es-PE,
    es-PR,es-PY,es-SV,es-US,es-UY,es-VE,et,fi,fr,fr-BE,fr-CA,fr-CH,fr-FR,fr-LU,gu,he,hi,hr,hu,id,is,it,it-CH,
    it-IT,ja,kk,ko,lt,lv,mk,mr,ms,ms-MY,mt,nl,nl-BE,nl-NL,no,no-NO,ny-NO,pl,pt,pt-BR,pt-PT,ro,ro-MD,ro-RO,
    ru,sk,sl,sq,sr,sv,ta,te,th,tr,uk,vi,x-KOK,zh-CN,zh-HK,zh-MO,zh-SG,zh-TW
@returns {TextOrTextList} Returns the requested information about the language codes. Empty string if tag is not found.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LOCALE_5907.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "French"};
@Locale([LanguageName]; "fr");
@example
REM {Returns "French(Canada"};
@Locale([LocaleName]; "fr-CA");

@Log.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the common logarithm (base 10) of any number greater than zero.

@param {number} value Number or number list. Number who's common logarithm will be returned. Must be larger than zero.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The log of number.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LOG.html | www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "returns 0.602059991327962";
@Log(4);
@example
REM "returns [0.6989700043360187, 0.7781512503836435, 0.8450980400142567]";
@Log(5,6,7);

@LowerCase.!doc:
@category:Text
Converts the uppercase letters in the specified string to lowercase.
@param {TextOrTextList} text  The string you want to convert to lowercase.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The text, converted to lowercase letters.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_LOWERCASE.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "juan mendoza"};
@LowerCase("Juan Mendoza");
@example
REM {Returns "juan" : "mendoza"};
@LowerCase("Juan" : "Mendoza");

@MailSend.!doc:
@category:Mail
@MailSend Composes a new mail memo based on the information you supply in the arguments list, and sends it to the recipients listed in the sendTo, copyTo, and blindcopyTo arguments.
@param {TextOrTextList} sendTo - Send To list
@param {TextOrTextList} copyTo - Copy To list
@param {TextOrTextList} blindCopyTo - Blind Copy To list
@param {string} subject - Subject of email
@param {string} remark - Remark appearing in front of email body
@param {TextOrTextList} bodyFields - Body of email taken from document fields
@param {any} flags - Flags for email
@returns {Promise<void>} - Promise that will resolve when MailSend is completed.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcl-software.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MAILSEND.html}

@Matches.!doc:
@category:Text
Tests a string for a pattern string. Because the pattern string can contain a number of "wildcard" characters
and logical symbols, you can test for complex character patterns.
@param {TextOrTextList} text The string you want to scan in quotes. You can also enter the field name of a field
that contains the string you want to scan; do not surround the field name in quotes.
@param {TextOrTextList} pattern The pattern you want to scan for in string surrounded by quotation marks.
May contain wildcard characters and symbols (see the following table). The following symbols require a preceding
backslash unless the pattern is enclosed in braces { } as a set: ?, *, &, !, |, \, +. The symbols require two
preceding backslashes instead of one if the pattern is specified as a literal. This is because the backslash is an
escape character in string literals, so "\?" passes "?" to the matching engine, where it is treated as a wildcard,
while "\\?" passes "\?" to the matching engine, where it is treated as a question mark character.
The wildcard characters and symbols are as follows:
- C Where C is any character. Matches any single, non-special character C (or c)
- ? Matches any single character
- * Matches any string (any number of characters)
- {ABC} Matches any character in set ABC
- {A-FL-R} Matches any character in the sets A...F and L...R
- +C Matches any number of occurrences of C (or c)
- ! Complements logical meaning of the pattern (logical NOT)
- | Performs logical OR of two patterns
- & Performs logical AND of two patterns

@returns {boolean} True if _text_ contains the pattern. False if _text_ does not contain the pattern.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MATCHES.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@Matches("A big test";"a?????test");
@example
REM {Returns 0};
@Matches("A big test";"a?test");
@example
REM {Returns error message, "Value cannot be a letter" if input contains any lowercase or uppercase letter between A and Z};
@If(@Matches(@Text(input);"+{!A-z}");@Success;@Failure("Value cannot be a letter"));

@Max.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the largest number in a single list, or the larger of two numbers or
number lists.

@param {number} values Number or number list.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The larger of the values provided. If the
parameters are number lists, Max returns a list that is the result of pair-wise computation on the list values.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MAX.html | www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "returns 6";
@Max(4,5,6);
@example
REM "returns [5, 9, 6, 7]";
@Max([5,8,6,7],[2,9,3]);

@Member.!doc:
@category:Lists
Given a value, finds its position in a text list.
@param value The value you want to find in _stringlist_.
@param stringlist The text list to search.
@returns Returns 0 if the _value_ is not contained in _stringlist_. Returns 1 to n if the value is contained in the stringlist,
where 1 to n is the position of the value in the stringlist.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MEMBER.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {This example returns 2};
@Member("Sales";"Finance":"Sales":"Service":"Legal");
@example
REM {This example returns 0};
@Member("Sales";"Finance":"Service":"Legal");

@Middle.!doc:
@category:Text
Returns any substring from the middle of a string. The middle is found by scanning the string from left to right,
and parameters determine where the middle begins and ends.
@param {TextOrTextList} text Any string
@param {number|string} start If a number, a character position in _text_ that indicates where you want the middle to begin,
always counting from left to right. The middle begins one character after the _start_.

If a string, a substring of _text_ that indicates where you want the middle to begin, always counting from
left to right. The middle begins one character after the end of _start_.
@param {number|string} end If a number, the number of characters that you want in the middle. If _end_ is negative, the middle
starts at _start_ and continues from right to left. If end is positive, the middle starts one character
past _start_ and continues from left to right.

If a string, a substring of _text_ that indicates the end of the middle. Returns all the characters between
_start_ and _end_.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The substring from the middle of _text_, which begins at the _start_ you specify and ends
at the _end_ you specify, or after _end_ characters have been reached.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MIDDLE.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "h C"};
@Middle("North Carolina";4;3);
@example
REM {Returns "Hello" : "This"};
@Middle("Hello world" : "This is the time"; 0; " ");

@MiddleBack.!doc:
@category:Text
Returns any substring from the middle of a string. The middle is found by scanning the string from right to left,
and parameters determine where the middle begins and ends.
@param {TextOrTextList} text Any string.
@param {number|string} start If a number, a character position in _text_ that indicates where you want the middle to begin, always
counting from right to left. The middle begins one character after the _start_. Always add 1 to this number; the end
of the string is marked by one non-visible character and must be counted in the offset.

If a string, a substring of _text_ that indicates where you want the middle to begin, always counting from right to left.
The middle begins one character after the end of start.
@param {number|string} end If a number, The number of characters that you want in the middle. If end is negative, the middle
starts at _start_ and continues from right to left. If end is positive, the middle starts one character
past _start_ and continues from left to right.

If a string, a substring of string that indicates the end of the middle. Returns all the characters between
_start_ and _end_.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The substring from the middle of _text_, which begins at the _start_ you specify and ends at
the _end_ you specify, or after _end_ characters have been reached.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MIDDLEBACK.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "Alt"};
@MiddleBack("Timothy Altman";" ";3);
@example
REM {Returns "searches the string"};
@MiddleBack("@MiddleBack searches the string from right to left"; "from"; -20);
@example
REM {Returns "world" : "time"};
@MiddleBack("Hello world" : "This is the time"; 0; " ");

@Min.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the smallest number in a single list, or the smaller of two numbers or
number lists.

@param {number} values Number or number list.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The smaller of the values provided. If the
parameters are number lists, Max returns a list that is the result of pair-wise computation on the list values.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MIN.html | www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "returns 4";
@Min(4,5,6);
@example
REM "returns [2, 8, 3, 7]";
@Min([5,8,6,7],[2,9,3]);

@Minute.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Extracts the number of the minutes from a specified Date.

@param {DateOrDateList} dateOrDateList The date, as a string, Date object, or Array of Date objects or strings, of the minutes you are trying to find.
@returns {NumberOrNumberList} Number or Number list. Minutes portion (or list of minutes) of the given date.
    Returns -1 if the time-date provided contains only a date and not a time value.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MINUTE.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 30};
@Minute([1/1/1900 1:30]);
@example
REM {Returns 58};
@Minute(@Date(95; 11; 20; 8; 58; 12));

@Modified.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Returns the time-date when the document was last modified.
@returns {Date|Error} Date. The date when the current document was last modified or error.data when the document or data is not available.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MODIFIED.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "Returns Mon May 22 2023 12:46:49 GMT-0400 (Eastern Daylight Time)";
@Modified();

@Modulo.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the remainder of a division operation.

@param {number} dividend Number or number list. The dividend (numerator) to be divided.
@param {number} divisor Number or number list. The divisor (denominator) to be divide dividend by.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The remainder of dividend divided by divisor. If the
parameters are number lists, mod returns a list that is the result of pair-wise computation on the list values.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MODULO.html | www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "returns 3";
@Modulo(7,4);
@example
REM "returns [3,2]";
@Modulo([7,5],[4,3]);

@Month.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Extracts the number of the month (1-12) from the specified date.

@param {DateOrDateList} dateOrDateList The date, as a string, Date object, or Array of Date objects or strings, of the month you are trying to find.
@returns {NumberOrNumberList} Number or number list. The number corresponding to the month.
    Returns -1 if the time-date provided contains only a time value and not a date.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_MONTH.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 12};
@Minute([12/1/1990]);
@example
REM {Returns 1};
@Minute(@Date(1900; 0; 31));

@Name.!doc:
@category:User Environment
Allows you to manipulate hierarchical names. You can abbreviate the canonical format of a name,
expand an abbreviated name to its canonical format, identify particular components within the name,
and reverse the order of the components so that you can categorize a view by hierarchical names.
@param {string} action Indicates what you want done to the name.
@param {TextOrTextList} name A user or server name, entered in any form (Notes/Domino determines the full hierarchical name
and then returns the requested components) or an LDAP AttributeType, ObjectClass, or Syntax name or a Domino® form,
subform, field, or data type name to be converted from LDAP to Domino® format or vice-versa.
@returns The second parameter formatted according to the first parameter as a Promise.
@see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_NAME.html|www.hcltechsw.com } for a list of possible actions.

@NameLookup.!doc:
@category:Directory
@willnotimplement:<strong>No plans to implement</strong>
Searches for each specified user name across all Domino® Directories and returns
a list of single text values for each specified user name.

@throws {Error} No plans to implement
@see For further information, see &nbsp; {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_NAMELOOKUP_7699.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@Narrow.!doc:
@category:Text
Converts full-pitch alphanumeric characters (double byte characters -- DBCS) in the specified string to half-pitch
alphanumeric characters (single byte characters -- SBCS). This function works in Japanese, Korean, Simplified Chinese,
and traditional Chinese environments. In the Japanese environment, this function can convert full-pitch Katakana as well.
@param {TextOrTextList} text The string that you want to convert to single byte characters.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The string converted to single byte characters.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_NARROW_1613.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "New York" as half-pitch characters to save space for displaying the string};
@Narrow("New York");
@example
REM {Returns the list "Tokyo" : "New York" as half-pitch characters to save space for displaying the string};
@Narrow("Tokyo" : "New York");

@NewLine.!doc:
@category:Text
Returns a new line (carriage return).
@returns {string} A new line character.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_NEWLINE.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "Hi };
REM {There"};
"Hi"+@NewLine+"There";

@No.!doc:
@category:Logical
Returns the number 0 (false).

@returns {number} The number 0 (false).
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_NO.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@NotesError.!doc:
@category:Information
Returns a Notes Error
@returns {Error} Notes Error
@see For further information, see &nbsp; {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ERROR.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@Nothing.!doc:
@category:Lists
Use with an &#64;Transform formula. Returns no list element (reducing the return list by one element). Not valid in any other context.
@returns Nothing or null. Returns nothing in an &#64;Transform formula, or null.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_NOTHING.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns a 2-element list whose values are 2 and 4 if the value of OriginalList is 4:-4:16};
@If(OriginalList = @Nothing; @Nothing;
@Transform(OriginalList; "x";
@If(x >= 0; @Sqrt(x); @Nothing)))

@Now.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Return the string representation of the current date and time.
The Notes parameters, flags and serverNames, are not implemented in VoltFormula at this time.

@returns {string} A string representation of the current date and time
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_NOW.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns '6/7/2024 5:00:00 PM' if today is June 7th, 2024 at 5pm};
@Now();

@OpenDocument.!doc:
@category:Open
Opens a document.
@param {boolean} [writeOrReadOnly]  A value of "1" opens the document in Edit mode. A value of "0" (the default) opens the document in Read-only mode.
@param {string} UNID The UNID (unique document ID) of the document you want to open. If you omit this parameter, Notes/Domino opens the currently selected document.
You can find a document's unique id on the Document IDs tab of the Document properties box. The UNID begins after "OF" on the first line and continues after
"ON" on the second line. Omit the colons.
@returns Promise that resolves to true if the document was opened.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_OPENDOCUMENT.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "Opens a document by UNID in read-only mode";
@Command([OpenDocument];"0";"F56ACC1F6F27155D8525686500603D43");

@OpenInNewWindow.!doc:
@category:Document
Opens the specified document within a new window.
To customize the window style, sknDialogWindowContainer, sknDialogWindowTitleContainer, and sknDialogWindowTitle skins need to be defined in the project.

@param {string} formFriendlyName. The name of the form to display in the dialog box.
@returns {void}
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_OPENINNEWWINDOW.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@OpenView.!doc:
@category:Open
Opens the specified view in the current database.
@param {string} viewName The name of the view you want to open. If you omit the view name, the database opens to its default view;
or, if the user has opened the database before, to the last view used by that person. If the database is already open to the specified
view, Notes/Domino makes that the first window.
@param {string} [key] Indicates which document you want Notes/Domino to scroll to when it opens viewName.
The key is a value that appears in the first sorted column of viewName. If you omit the key, no document is selected.
@returns Promise that resolves to true if the view was open.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_OPENVIEW.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "Opens the view 'MainTopic' in the current database";
@Command([OpenView]; "MainTopic");

@Pi.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the constant value pi, accurate to fifteen decimal places. The value pi
is the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter.

@returns {number} Returns the constant value pi, accurate to fifteen decimal places. 3.141592653589793
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_PI.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
and {@link https://www.oasis-open.org/committees/download.php/16826/openformula-spec-20060221.html#PI|www.oasis-open.org}

@Platform.!doc:
@category:User Environment
Returns the name of the currently running platform version of Domino.
@param {string} [spec] - Returns more detailed information; for example,
the version number in addition to the name of the platform.
@returns {Promise<TextOrTextList>} Without the parameter, returns a Promise that resolves to the name of the platform.
When you use the [SPECIFIC] keyword, &#64;Platform returns a Promise that resolves to a text list.
The text list contains the following items:
- PrimaryOSName - The detailed platform name.
- PrimaryOSVersionNumber - The current version number of the primary operating system if available. For the UNIX™ platform, &#64;Platform([SPECIFIC]) returns only the specific platform name, not the version number.

@Power.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the result of a number raised to a power.

@param {number} base Number or number list. The value that you want raised to exponent. May be
    positive or negative.
@param {number} exponent Number or number list. The power to which the base number is raised.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The value of base raised to the power of exponent. If the parameters are arrays,
returns an array that is the result of pair-wise computation on the array values.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_POWER.html | www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM "returns 16";
@Power(4,2);
@example
REM "returns [25, 36]";
@Power([5,6],[2,2]);

@Prompt.!doc:
@category:Document
Get html to generate a prompt.
@param {string} style The type of prompt to generate
@param {string} title The title for the prompt
@param {string} prompt Optional. Text to display with the prompt
@param {string} defaultChoice Optional. Default choice to select when the prompt is displayed.
@param {Array} choiceList Optional. The list of avaliable choices
@returns A promise that will inject the code for the prompt into the document.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_PROMPT.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@ProperCase.!doc:
@category:Text
Converts the words in a string to proper-name capitalization: the first letter of each word becomes uppercase,
all others become lowercase.
@param {TextOrTextList} text The string you want to convert.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The _text_, converted to proper-name capitalization.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_PROPERCASE.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "Every Child Loves Toys"};
@ProperCase("every CHILD LOves toys");
@example
REM {Returns "Robert" : "Smith"};
@ProperCase("ROBERT" : "SMITH");

@Random.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Generates a random number between 0 and 1, inclusive by calling open formula RAND

@returns {number} Random number between 0 and 1, inclusive.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_RANDOM.html | www.hcltechsw.com }

@ReloadWindow.!doc:
@category:Window
Reloads the current application or form
Depending on the application platform the behavior may vary
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_RELOADWINDOW_COMMAND.html | hcltechsw.com}

@Repeat.!doc:
@category:Text
Repeats a string a specified number of times.
@param {TextOrTextList} text The string you want to repeat.
@param {number} number The number of times you want to repeat string.
@param {number} [maxchar] The maximum number of characters you want returned. Truncates the result to this number.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The _text_, repeated _number_ times until _maxchar_ (if specified) is reached.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_REPEAT.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "HelloHelloHello"};
@Repeat("Hello";3);
@example
REM {Returns "ByeBy"};
@Repeat("Bye";2;5);

@Replace.!doc:
@category:Lists
Performs a find-and-replace operation on a text list.

@param {string[]} sourcelist The list whose values you want to scan.
@param {string[]} fromlist A list containing the values that you want to replace.
@param {string[]} tolist A list containing the replacement values.
@returns {string[]} The _sourcelist_, with any values from _fromlist_ replaced by the corresponding value in _tolist_. If none of the values in _fromlist_ matched the values in _sourcelist_, then _sourcelist_ is returned unaltered.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_REPLACE.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "Red":"Black":"Yellow":"Green"};
@Replace("Red":"Orange":"Yellow":"Green";"Orange":"Blue";"Black":"Brown");

@ReplaceSubstring.!doc:
@category:Text
Replaces specific words or phrases in a string with new words or phrases that you specify. Case sensitive.
@param {TextOrTextList} source The string whose contents you want to modify.
@param {TextOrTextList} from A list containing the words or phrases that you want to replace.
@param {TextOrTextList} to A list containing the replacement words or phrases.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The _source_, with any values from _from_ replaced by the corresponding value in _to_. If none of the values
in _from_ matched the values in _source_, then _source_ is returned unaltered.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_REPLACESUBSTRING.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "I hate apples"};
@ReplaceSubstring( "I like apples" ; "like" ; "hate" );
@example
REM {Returns "I hate peaches"};
@ReplaceSubstring( "I like apples" ; "like" : "apples" ; "hate" : "peaches");
@example
REM {Returns "He hates apples" : "He hates bananas"};
@ReplaceSubstring("I like apples" : "I like bananas"; "like" : "I"; "hates" : "He")

@Responses.!doc:
@category:Document
Returns the number of responses (in the current view) to the document.
@returns {number} value. The number of responses to the document.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_RESPONSES.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 5 if there are five responses to the document.};
@Responses;
@example
REM {Returns the string 'No one has responded to this document' if there are no responses to the current document; otherwise a blank is returned.};
@If(@Responses=0; "No one has responded to this document"; " ");

@RestfulAPI.!doc:
@category:Network
Function to call a Restful API.
@param {string} url - The URL of the REST service.
@param {string} method - The HTTP method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.).
@param {string} headers - Optional headers to include in the request as a JSON string.
@param {string} body - Optional body for POST, PUT, or PATCH requests as a JSON string.
@param {string} additionalRequestParams - Optional additional request parameters as a JSON string.
@returns {Promise<any>} - A promise that resolves to the response data or rejects with an error.
@example
const authUrl = 'https://keep-server.qs.hcllabs.net/api/v1/auth';
const authHeaders = '{ "accept": "application/json", "Content-Type": "application/json" }';
let authBody = '{ "username": "abc", "password": "xyz" }';

const authResponse = await RestfulAPI(authUrl, 'POST', authHeaders, authBody);
console.log(authResponse);

@Return.!doc:
@category:Logical
Immediately stops the execution of a formula and returns the specified value.
This is useful when you only want the remainder of the formula to be executed
only if certain conditions are True.

@param {*} value The value to return.
@returns {*} The value.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_RETURN.html | www.hcltechsw.com}

@Right.!doc:
@category:Text
Returns the rightmost characters in the string. You can specify the number of rightmost characters you want returned,
or you can indicate that you want all the characters following a specific substring.
@param {TextOrTextList} text The string whose rightmost characters you want to find.
@param {string|number} param If a number, the number of characters to return. If the number is 2, the last two characters of _text_
are returned; if the number is 5, the last five characters are returned, and so on.

If a string, a substring of _text_. Returns all of the characters to the right of _param_. It finds
_param_ by searching _text_ from left to right.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The rightmost characters in _text_. The number of characters returned is determined by _param_.
Returns "" if _param_ is not found in _text_.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_RIGHT.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "ace"};
@Right("Lennard Wallace";3);
@example
REM {Returns "Wallace"};
@Right("Lennard Wallace";" ");

@RightBack.!doc:
@category:Text
Returns the rightmost characters in a string.
@param {TextOrTextList} text The string whose rightmost characters you want to find.
@param {number| string} param If a number, counting from left to right, the number of characters to skip. All the characters
following that number are returned.

If a string, A substring of _text_. Returns all the characters following _param_. It finds
_param_ by searching _text_ from right to left.
@returns {TextOrTextList} The rightmost characters in _text_. The number of characters returned is determined by _param_.
@see For more information see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_RIGHTBACK.html|www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns "nard Wallace"};
@RightBack("Lennard Wallace";3);
@example
REM {Returns "Wallace"};
@RightBack("Lennard Wallace";" ");

@Round.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Rounds the designated number to the nearest whole number; if an additional
number is specified, it is used as the rounding factor.

@param {number} number Number or number list. Numbers to be rounded.
@param {number} factor Number. Optional. The rounding factor to use. If you don't specify a factor,
the number is rounded to the nearest whole number.
@returns {number} Number or number list. The value of number, rounded to the specified factor or
to the nearest whole number. If number is a list, each number in the list is
rounded to the specified factor or to the nearest whole number.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_ROUND.html | www.hcltechsw.com }

@Second.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Extracts the number of the seconds from a specified Date.
This function presumes that leap seconds never exist.

@param {DateOrDateList} dateOrDateList The date, as a string, Date object, or Array of Date objects or strings, of the seconds you are trying to find.
@returns {NumberOrNumberList} Number or Number list. Seconds portion (or list of seconds) of the given date.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_SECOND.html | www.hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM {Returns 0};
@Second("1/1/1900");
@example
REM {Returns 59};
@Second("11/20/95 8:58:59");
@example
REM {Returns 12};
@Second(@Date(95; 11; 20; 8; 58; 12));

@Select.!doc:
@category:Lists
Returns the value that appears in the number position. If the number is greater
than the number of values, &#64;Select returns the last value in the list. If
the value in the number position is a list, returns the entire list contained
within the value.
@param {number} position The position of the value you want to retrieve.
@param {NumberOrNumberList|TextOrTextList|DateOrDateList} values Any number of values, separated by
semicolons. A value may be a number, text, time-date, or a number list, text list, or time-date list.
@returns The value that appears in the number position.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_SELECT_AT.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {Returns 2};
@Select(2;1;2;3);
@example
REM {Returns Apr:May:Jun};
@Select(2;"Jan":"Feb":"Mar";"Apr":"May":"Jun";"Jul":"August":"Sep";"Oct":"Nov":"Dec");

@SelectDocuments.!doc:
@category:Database
Returns a Promise that can be resolved to an array of selected documents.
@param {string} formula - Selection formula.
@param {String} formName optional parameter. If not specified, form from the current document is used.
@returns {Promise<any[]>} - Promise that will resolve to the selected documents.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_SELECT.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@Set.!doc:
@category:Formula
Assigns a value to a temporary variable for use within a formula.
@param {string} variableName The name of a temporary variable.
@param {*} value Text, number, time-date, time-date range, or list thereof. The value you want to give to variableName.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_SET.html|www.hcltechsw.com }
@example
REM {Assigns FirstName and LastName to the first two elements of a list named FullName};
FirstName := "Foo";
LastName := "Bar";
@Set("FullName"; FirstName : LastName);

@SetDocField.!doc:
@category:Database
Given the unique ID of a document, sets the value of a specific field on that
document. The document must reside in the current database.
@param {string} documentUNID The unique ID of a document.
@param {string} fieldName The name of a field in the current document.
@param {*} fieldValue The value to set the field.
@returns Promise that resolves when the field has been set.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_SETDOCFIELD.html|www.hcltechsw.com }

@SetEnvironment.!doc:
@category:Miscellaneous
Sets an environment variable.
@param {string} key The name of the environment variable.
@param {string} value The value of the environment variable.
@see For further information, see {@link https://help.hcltechsw.com/dom_designer/14.0.0/basic/H_SETENVIRONMENT.html | hcltechsw.com}
@example
REM "Sets the value of the environment variable 'myVar' to 'myValue'";
@SetEnvironment("myVar", "myValue");

@SetField.!doc:
@category:Document
Assigns a value to a field, as per the API context (db or local), either on document or local DOM.
If context is db, the value is stored within a document (use @Set for temporary variables).
This is similar to using the FIELD keyword, except that @SetField
can be used within another @function. If the field does not exist, this
command creates it and applies the specified value to it.

